      <section id="sect-00033">
      <title>Math and Hockey</title>
      <para id="para-00043">Hockey is full of math from obvious components such as scoring and statistics to the shape of the rink and the angles involved in puck movement.</para>
      <para id="para-00044">Collegiate and professional hockey games are 60 minutes long and are divided into three periods of 20 (60/3) minutes each. At any one time, there are five players and one goalie on the ice for each team. If a player is called on a penalty and is placed in the penalty box, that team now has four players, which is 20% less players on the ice competing against five opponents. In some instances, a team may have two players in the penalty box at one time, resulting in three players, or 40% less players on the ice compared to a full team. Being one player down for a 2-minute penalty or potentially 5 minutes for a major penalty leads to an imbalance on the ice and calls for a quick change of offense and defense strategy.</para>
      <section id="sect-00034">
      <title>Rink Composition—North American</title>
      <para id="para-00103">An ice rink is comprised of various geometrical shapes, each with precise dimensions.</para>
      <list list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic" id="list-00029">
      <item>Research the dimensions of a hockey rink and draw an accurate scale model on graph paper. Be sure to include the scale for your model and indicate all units.<newline/>
      Answer:
      <figure id="fig-00004">
      <media alt="Insert Alt Text">
      <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CS_Figure_13_05_003.png"/>
      </media>
      </figure></item>
      <item>List the shapes and the numbers of each kind of hockey rink. You should find four different shapes, some with multiple dimensions.<newline/>
      Answer: A North American ice hockey rink is comprised of the following shapes:
      <list bullet-style="bulleted" id="list-00030">
      <item>Rectangle: A center rectangle measuring 50 feet long by 44 feet wide. Each width end of the center rectangle contains a side rectangle 30 feet long by 44 feet wide.</item>
      <item>Trapezoid: At the end of each of the side rectangles, is what is referred to as a trapezoid, with length 11 feet narrowing to a width of 6 feet. Mathematically, the trapezoid is not a geometric trapezoid as the non-parallel sides are curved rather than straight.</item>
      <item>Circle: There are five face-off circles, each with a radius of 15 feet.</item>
      <item>Semi-circle: There are three semi-circles, two in front of each goal post with a radius of 4 feet and one in the middle of the ice rink.</item>
      </list></item>
      <item>Describe the shape and dimensions of a hockey puck using geometric vocabulary.<newline/>
      Answer: A hockey puck is in the shape of a short right circular cylinder with a height of 1 inch and diameter of 3 inches.</item>
      </list>
      </section>
      <section id="sect-00035">
      <title>Statistics</title>
      <para id="para-00104">Using an Internet search, select two top hockey players from the same league to answer the following questions:</para>
      <list list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic" start-value="4" id="list-00031">
      <item>Write a paragraph sharing a minimum of five statistics for each player you have selected. Describe how each of the statistics are calculated and what each statistic means.</item>
      <item>Write a paragraph comparing the two players and determine who you believe is the better player. Support your choice.</item>
       </list>
      </section>
